]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:People who lost United States citizenship]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ashdown House]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:American Anglicans]]\n[[Category:20th-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Converts to Anglicanism from Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Christians from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Christians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:English people of American descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:People from Crouch End]]\n[[Category:People from Maida Vale]]\n[[Category:People from Uccle]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Norwalk, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Writers from Norwalk, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the European Schools]]\n", "name_user": "TAVTNESHAY", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boris_Johnson"}
{"title_page": "Mercury(II) fulminate", "text_new": "{{chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 477000105\n| ImageFile = <chem>{}^{-}O-\\overset{+}{N}#C-Hg-C#\\overset{+}{N}-O^{-}</chem>\n| ImageFile1 = Mercury-fulminate-3D-vdW.png\n| ImageFile2 = Mercury-fulminate-xtal-3D-vdW.png\n| ImageFile3 = Mercuryfulminate puryfied.jpg\n| IUPACName = \n| OtherNames = Fulminated Mercury\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 9197626\n| InChI = 1/2CNO.Hg/c2*1-2-3;/rC2HgN2O2/c6-4-1-3-2-5-7\n| InChIKey = MHWLNQBTOIYJJP-HZIBCBEIAJ\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/2CNO.Hg/c2*1-2-3;\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = MHWLNQBTOIYJJP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|changed|??}}\n| CASNo = 628-86-4\n| PubChem = 11022444\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 39152\n| SMILES = [O-][N+]#C[Hg]C#[N+][O-]\n}}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = \tC<sub>2</sub>N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>Hg\n| MolarMass = 284.624 g/mol\n| Appearance = Grey, Pale Brown, or White Crystalline solid\n| Density = 4.42 g/cm<sup>3</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 160\n| BoilingPtC = 356.6\n| Solubility = slightly soluble\n| SolubleOther = soluble in [[ethanol]], [[ammonia]]\n  }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Explosive\n| ShockSens = High\n| FrictionSens = High\n| DetonationV = 4250 m/s\n| REFactor = \n}}\n|Section4={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards = Highly Toxic, Shock Sensitive Explosive\n| NFPA-H = 4\n| NFPA-F = 1\n| NFPA-R = 4\n| AutoignitionPtC = 170\n| AutoignitionPt_notes = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Mercury(II) fulminate''', or '''Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub>''', is a [[primary explosive]]. It is highly sensitive to [[friction]], heat and [[shock (mechanics)|shock]] and is mainly used as a trigger for other explosives in [[percussion cap]]s and [[blasting cap]]s. [[Mercury(II) cyanate]], though its empirical formula is identical, has a different atomic arrangement; the [[cyanate]] and [[fulminate]] [[Ion#Anions and cations|anions]] are [[isomer]]s.\n\nFirst used as a [[priming composition]] in small copper caps beginning in the 1820s, mercury fulminate quickly replaced [[flint]]s as a means to ignite [[black powder]] charges in [[Muzzleloader|muzzle-loading]] [[firearm]]s. Later, during the late 19th century and most of the 20th century, mercury fulminate or [[potassium chlorate]] became widely used in [[Centerfire ammunition#Centerfire primers|primers]] for [[Cartridge (firearms)|self-contained rifle and pistol ammunition]]. Mercury fulminate has the distinct advantage over potassium chlorate of being non-corrosive, but it is known to weaken with time, by decomposing into its  constituent elements.  The reduced mercury which results forms amalgams with cartridge brass, weakening it, as well.  Today, mercury fulminate has been replaced in primers by more efficient chemical substances. These are non-corrosive, less toxic and more stable over time; they include [[lead azide]], [[lead styphnate]] and [[tetrazene]] derivatives. In addition, none of these compounds require [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] for manufacture, supplies of which can be unreliable in wartime.\n\n==Preparation==\nMercury(II) fulminate is prepared by dissolving [[mercury (element)|mercury]] in [[nitric acid]] and adding [[ethanol]] to the solution. It was first prepared by [[Edward Charles Howard]] in 1800.<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = On a New Fulminating Mercury\n| author = Edward Howard\n| journal = [[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London]]\n| year = 1800\n| volume = 90\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 204\u2013238\n| doi = 10.1098/rstl.1800.0012\n}}</ref> The [[crystal structure]] of this compound was only determined in 2007.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=W. Beck |author2=J. Evers |author3=M. G\u00f6bel |author4=G. Oehlinger |author5=T. M. Klap\u00f6tke | title = The Crystal and Molecular Structure of Mercury Fulminate (Knallquecksilber) | year = 2007 | journal = [[Zeitschrift f\u00fcr anorganische und allgemeine Chemie]] | volume = 633 | issue = 9 | pages = 1417\u20131422 | doi = 10.1002/zaac.200700176}}</ref>\n\n[[Silver fulminate]] can be prepared in a similar way, but this [[salt (chemistry)|salt]] is even more unstable than mercury fulminate; it can even explode under water and is impossible to accumulate in large amounts because it detonates under its own weight.\n\n==Decomposition==\nThe thermal decomposition of mercury(II) fulminate can begin at temperatures as low as 100&nbsp;\u00b0C, though it proceeds at a much higher rate with increasing temperature.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1098/rspa.1933.0040|title=Thermal decomposition and detonation of mercury fulminate|author1=W. E. Garner|author2=H. R. Hailes|lastauthoramp=yes|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London|volume=139|issue=1\u20133|year=1933|pages=1\u201340|url=http://rspa.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/139/839/576.full.pdf+html|accessdate=2013-03-11|bibcode=1933CP....334..128S|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304044022/http://rspa.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/139/839/576.full.pdf+html|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA possible reaction for the decomposition of mercury(II) fulminate yields [[carbon dioxide]] gas, [[nitrogen]] gas, and a combination of relatively stable mercury salts.\n:4 Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 2 CO<sub>2</sub> +  N<sub>2</sub> +  HgO + 3 Hg(OCN)CN\n:Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 2 CO +  N<sub>2</sub> +   Hg  \n:Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 :Hg(OCN)<sub>2</sub> ([[cyanate]] or / and [[isocyanate]])\n:2 Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 2 CO<sub>2</sub> +  N<sub>2</sub> +  Hg + Hg(CN)<sub>2</sub> ([[mercury(II) cyanide]])\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the 1955 comedy film \"[[Mister Roberts (1955 film)|Mister Roberts]]\", Ensign Frank Pulver test fires a fulminate of mercury firecracker and blows up the ship's laundry spreading soap suds across three decks.   \n\nIn the TV Western series \"[[Have Gun - Will Travel]]\", Season 4 Episode 10 \"Crowbait\", Russell Collins plays prospector Crowbait, who is packing fulminated Mercury. Paladin worries about being blown up while taking a pack sack off.\n\nIn the episode of [[Breaking Bad]] titled \"[[Crazy Handful of Nothin']]\", Walter White used mercury (II) fulminate to blow up Tuco Salamanca's headquarters.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fulminic acid]]\n* [[Potassium fulminate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mercury(II) fulminate}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060425193836/http://www.npi.gov.au/database/substance-info/profiles/53.html National Pollutant Inventory - Mercury and compounds Fact Sheet]\n*{{cite news | title = 300 years after discovery, structure of mercury fulminate finally determined | publisher = physorg.com | url = http://www.physorg.com/news107176552.html | date = 24 August 2007}}\n{{Mercury compounds}}\n\n[[Category:Mercury(II) compounds]]\n[[Category:Fulminates]]\n[[Category:Explosive chemicals]]\n", "text_old": "{{chembox\n| Verifiedfields = changed\n| Watchedfields = changed\n| verifiedrevid = 477000105\n| ImageFile = <chem>{}^{-}O-\\overset{+}{N}#C-Hg-C#\\overset{+}{N}-O^{-}</chem>\n| ImageFile1 = Mercury-fulminate-3D-vdW.png\n| ImageFile2 = Mercury-fulminate-xtal-3D-vdW.png\n| ImageFile3 = Mercuryfulminate puryfied.jpg\n| IUPACName = \n| OtherNames = Fulminated Mercury\n|Section1={{Chembox Identifiers\n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|correct|chemspider}}\n| ChemSpiderID = 9197626\n| InChI = 1/2CNO.Hg/c2*1-2-3;/rC2HgN2O2/c6-4-1-3-2-5-7\n| InChIKey = MHWLNQBTOIYJJP-HZIBCBEIAJ\n| StdInChI_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChI = 1S/2CNO.Hg/c2*1-2-3;\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = {{stdinchicite|correct|chemspider}}\n| StdInChIKey = MHWLNQBTOIYJJP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|changed|??}}\n| CASNo = 628-86-4\n| PubChem = 11022444\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 39152\n| SMILES = [O-][N+]#C[Hg]C#[N+][O-]\n}}\n|Section2={{Chembox Properties\n| Formula = \tC<sub>2</sub>N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>2</sub>Hg\n| MolarMass = 284.624 g/mol\n| Appearance = Grey, Pale Brown, or White Crystalline solid\n| Density = 4.42 g/cm<sup>3</sup>\n| MeltingPtC = 160\n| BoilingPtC = 356.6\n| Solubility = slightly soluble\n| SolubleOther = soluble in [[ethanol]], [[ammonia]]\n  }}\n|Section3={{Chembox Explosive\n| ShockSens = High\n| FrictionSens = High\n| DetonationV = 4250 m/s\n| REFactor = \n}}\n|Section4={{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards = Highly Toxic, Shock Sensitive Explosive\n| NFPA-H = 4\n| NFPA-F = 1\n| NFPA-R = 4\n| AutoignitionPtC = 170\n| AutoignitionPt_notes = \n  }}\n}}\n'''Mercury(II) fulminate''', or '''Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub>''', is a [[primary explosive]]. It is highly sensitive to [[friction]], heat and [[shock (mechanics)|shock]] and is mainly used as a trigger for other explosives in [[percussion cap]]s and [[blasting cap]]s. [[Mercury(II) cyanate]], though its empirical formula is identical, has a different atomic arrangement; the [[cyanate]] and [[fulminate]] [[Ion#Anions and cations|anions]] are [[isomer]]s.\n\nFirst used as a [[priming composition]] in small copper caps beginning in the 1820s, mercury fulminate quickly replaced [[flint]]s as a means to ignite [[black powder]] charges in [[Muzzleloader|muzzle-loading]] [[firearm]]s. Later, during the late 19th century and most of the 20th century, mercury fulminate or [[potassium chlorate]] became widely used in [[Centerfire ammunition#Centerfire primers|primers]] for [[Cartridge (firearms)|self-contained rifle and pistol ammunition]]. Mercury fulminate has the distinct advantage over potassium chlorate of being non-corrosive, but it is known to weaken with time, by decomposing into its  constituent elements.  The reduced mercury which results forms amalgams with cartridge brass, weakening it, as well.  Today, mercury fulminate has been replaced in primers by more efficient chemical substances. These are non-corrosive, less toxic and more stable over time; they include [[lead azide]], [[lead styphnate]] and [[tetrazene]] derivatives. In addition, none of these compounds require [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] for manufacture, supplies of which can be unreliable in wartime.\n\n==Preparation==\nMercury(II) fulminate is prepared by dissolving [[mercury (element)|mercury]] in [[nitric acid]] and adding [[ethanol]] to the solution. It was first prepared by [[Edward Charles Howard]] in 1800.<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = On a New Fulminating Mercury\n| author = Edward Howard\n| journal = [[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London]]\n| year = 1800\n| volume = 90\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 204\u2013238\n| doi = 10.1098/rstl.1800.0012\n}}</ref> The [[crystal structure]] of this compound was only determined in 2007.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=W. Beck |author2=J. Evers |author3=M. G\u00f6bel |author4=G. Oehlinger |author5=T. M. Klap\u00f6tke | title = The Crystal and Molecular Structure of Mercury Fulminate (Knallquecksilber) | year = 2007 | journal = [[Zeitschrift f\u00fcr anorganische und allgemeine Chemie]] | volume = 633 | issue = 9 | pages = 1417\u20131422 | doi = 10.1002/zaac.200700176}}</ref>\n\n[[Silver fulminate]] can be prepared in a similar way, but this [[salt (chemistry)|salt]] is even more unstable than mercury fulminate; it can even explode under water and is impossible to accumulate in large amounts because it detonates under its own weight.\n\n==Decomposition==\nThe thermal decomposition of mercury(II) fulminate can begin at temperatures as low as 100&nbsp;\u00b0C, though it proceeds at a much higher rate with increasing temperature.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1098/rspa.1933.0040|title=Thermal decomposition and detonation of mercury fulminate|author1=W. E. Garner|author2=H. R. Hailes|lastauthoramp=yes|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London|volume=139|issue=1\u20133|year=1933|pages=1\u201340|url=http://rspa.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/139/839/576.full.pdf+html|accessdate=2013-03-11|bibcode=1933CP....334..128S|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304044022/http://rspa.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/139/839/576.full.pdf+html|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA possible reaction for the decomposition of mercury(II) fulminate yields [[carbon dioxide]] gas, [[nitrogen]] gas, and a combination of relatively stable mercury salts.\n:4 Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 2 CO<sub>2</sub> +  N<sub>2</sub> +  HgO + 3 Hg(OCN)CN\n:Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 2 CO +  N<sub>2</sub> +   Hg  \n:Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 :Hg(OCN)<sub>2</sub> ([[cyanate]] or / and [[isocyanate]])\n:2 Hg(CNO)<sub>2</sub> \u2192 2 CO<sub>2</sub> +  N<sub>2</sub> +  Hg + Hg(CN)<sub>2</sub> ([[mercury(II) cyanide]])\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the 1955 comedy film \"[[Mister Roberts (1955 film)|Mister Roberts ]]\", Ensign Frank Pulver test fires a fulminate of mercury firecracker and blows up the ship's laundry spreading soap suds across three decks.   \n\nIn the episode of Breaking Bad titled \"[[Crazy Handful of Nothin']]\", Walter White used mercury (II) fulminate to blow up Tuco Salamanca's headquarters.\n\n\u201cHave Gun Will Travel\u201d, Season 4 Episode 10 \u201cCrowbait\u201d. Russell Collins plays prospector Crowbait, who is packing fulminated Mercury. Paladin worries about being blown up while taking a pack sack off.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fulminic acid]]\n* [[Potassium fulminate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mercury(II) fulminate}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060425193836/http://www.npi.gov.au/database/substance-info/profiles/53.html National Pollutant Inventory - Mercury and compounds Fact Sheet]\n*{{cite news | title = 300 years after discovery, structure of mercury fulminate finally determined | publisher = physorg.com | url = http://www.physorg.com/news107176552.html | date = 24 August 2007}}\n{{Mercury compounds}}\n\n[[Category:Mercury(II) compounds]]\n[[Category:Fulminates]]\n[[Category:Explosive chemicals]]\n", "name_user": "Richard Stephens", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:Added links to TV shows and reordered to chronological.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercury(II)_fulminate"}
{"title_page": "The African Doctor", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The African Doctor \n| film_name      = Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont\n| image          = Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Julien Rambaldi]]\n| producer       = Pauline Duhault <br> Olivier Delbosc <br>Marc Missonnier\n| screenplay     = Julien Rambaldi<br>[[Kamini (musician)|Kamini]]<br>[[Beno\u00eet Graffin]]\n| based on       =\n| starring       = \n| music          = Emmanuel Rambaldi\n| cinematography = Yannick Ressigeac \n| editing        = Stephane Pereira\n| studio         = E.D.I. Films <br> Moana Films <br> Curiosa Films<br>Cin\u00e9france<br>[[TF1 Films Production]]\n| distributor    = Mars Films \n| released       = {{film date|2016|6|8|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $4.4 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fBIENVENUEMARLYG01&country=FR&wk=2016W24&id=_fBIENVENUEMARLYG01&p=.htm|title=Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont (2016)- Box-Office Mojo|publisher=|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The African Doctor''''' (original title: '''''Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont''''') is a 2016 French [[comedy-drama film]] based on the life of the father of the musician [[Kamini (musician)|Kamini]], co-written by Kamini and directed by Julien Rambaldi. It stars [[Marc Zinga]] and [[A\u00efssa Ma\u00efga]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/cinema/actualite-cinema/video-bienvenue-a-marly-gomont-kamini-star-en-picardie-08-06-2016-5865439.php|title=VIDEO. \"Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont\" : Kamini, star en Picardie |work=[[Le Parisien]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/nord-pas-de-calais/bienvenue-marly-gomont-faut-il-aller-voir-le-film-insipre-de-la-vie-de-kamini-1016199.html|title=\"Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont\" : faut-il aller voir le film insipr\u00e9 de la vie de Kamini ? |work=[[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]]}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nSeyolo Zantoko has just graduated from a French medical school; he was the only African man in his class and circle of friends. After completing his medical school, he turned down his job at Zaire as a personal physician of President Joseph-Desir\u00e9 Mobutu, as+++\u00e7\u00e7\u00e7\u00f1. n  he wanted to avoid the corruption associated with his country. Instead, he is hired by the mayor of a small village, Marly-Gomont, in northern France. He tells his family that he got a job in a city north of Paris, France. His wife Anne and their two children, Sivi and Kamini, are disappointed to learn that they are living in a rural village, far from the excitement of Paris. His decision to live in France is mainly motivated by the hope of a better education for his children, but he also hopes to apply for French citizenship. Seyolo and his family struggle to adapt to new life as locals - unfamiliar with African professionals - fear newcomers, children are bullied at school, and Seyolo's practice struggles to survive as locals prefer to go to the next village whenever they need a doctor, instead of being visited by a \"wizard\". Seyolo and Anne have a heated argument in front of relatives who have come for a visit, during which Seyolo reluctantly promises that they will eventually move to Brussels, where some of their relatives live. However, Seyolo and his family end up winning the trust of the villagers, and his practice becomes a success after he delivers the baby to a local farmer.\n\nFollowing Seyolo's reputation and popularity, he tells the mayor that he wants to stay in Marly-Gomont for the long term. That same evening, the mayor and his wife are having dinner at the Zantokos' house, and the mayor mentions his happiness that Seyolo is in the village. Anne is shocked and angry at this revelation, for Seyolo had promised to move to Brussels and had not told Anne that he had accepted the mayor's request to stay in Marly-Gomont. Anne leaves to stay in Brussels with her family and the couple's relationship is in danger.\n\nMeanwhile, in Marly-Gomont, Seyolo is arrested by French police for immigration irregularities, days before his French citizenship application is approved, and he is forced to stop working. Anne finally returns and agrees to stay with Seyolo in Marly-Gomont. The only hope for Seyolo and his family is that the current mayor will be reelected, although his opponent, Lavigne, is leading the polls and is determined to prevent Seyolo from practicing in the village, preferring to hire a doctor of French origin. . However, Sivi is a talented soccer player and wins the hearts of the community, helping the local team make progress in the league alone. Seyolo and his children devise a plan to show residents that if Lavigne wins the election, the family will have to leave Marly-Gomont. Residents, upset over the prospect of losing the best football player, end up voting, and the incumbent mayor is reelected. Finally, the local school children play a play that re-enacts the arrival and eventual acceptance of Seyolo and his family, and they realize that they are loved by the entire community (except Lavigne, who leaves before the end of the show). Seyolo's office reopens and the family remains in Marly-Gomont.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Marc Zinga]] as Seyolo Zantoko\n* [[A\u00efssa Ma\u00efga]] as Anne Zantoko\n* Bayron Lebli as [[Kamini (musician)|Kamini Zantoko]]\n* M\u00e9dina Diarra as Sivi Zantoko\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]] as Jean\n* [[Jonathan Lambert (actor)|Jonathan Lambert]] as Lavigne\n* [[Mata Gabin]] as Mado\n* [[Sylvestre Amoussou]] as Uncle Beki\n* [[Riton Liebman]] as The driving teacher\n\n==See also==\n* [[Marly-Gomont (song)]], [[Kamini (musician)|Kamini]]'s ode to the small, rural village in Northern France where he grew up, Marly-Gomont. In the song, Kamini laments being from the only black family in town. The song became an Internet phenomenon and a number-one single in France.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|5555502}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:African Doctor, The}}\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films about race and ethnicity]]\n[[Category:Fictional physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The African Doctor \n| film_name      = Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont\n| image          = Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Julien Rambaldi]]\n| producer       = Pauline Duhault <br> Olivier Delbosc <br>Marc Missonnier\n| screenplay     = Julien Rambaldi<br>[[Kamini (musician)|Kamini]]<br>[[Beno\u00eet Graffin]]\n| based on       =\n| starring       = \n| music          = Emmanuel Rambaldi\n| cinematography = Yannick Ressigeac \n| editing        = Stephane Pereira\n| studio         = E.D.I. Films <br> Moana Films <br> Curiosa Films<br>Cin\u00e9france<br>[[TF1 Films Production]]\n| distributor    = Mars Films \n| released       = {{film date|2016|6|8|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $4.4 million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fBIENVENUEMARLYG01&country=FR&wk=2016W24&id=_fBIENVENUEMARLYG01&p=.htm|title=Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont (2016)- Box-Office Mojo|publisher=|accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The African Doctor''''' (original title: '''''Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont''''') is a 2016 French [[comedy-drama film]] based on the life of the father of the musician [[Kamini (musician)|Kamini]], co-written by Kamini and directed by Julien Rambaldi. It stars [[Marc Zinga]] and [[A\u00efssa Ma\u00efga]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/cinema/actualite-cinema/video-bienvenue-a-marly-gomont-kamini-star-en-picardie-08-06-2016-5865439.php|title=VIDEO. \"Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont\" : Kamini, star en Picardie |work=[[Le Parisien]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://france3-regions.francetvinfo.fr/nord-pas-de-calais/bienvenue-marly-gomont-faut-il-aller-voir-le-film-insipre-de-la-vie-de-kamini-1016199.html|title=\"Bienvenue \u00e0 Marly-Gomont\" : faut-il aller voir le film insipr\u00e9 de la vie de Kamini ? |work=[[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]]}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nSeyolo Zantoko has just graduated from a French medical school; he was the only African man in his class and circle of friends. After completing his medical school, he turned down his job at Zaire as a personal physician of President Joseph-Desir\u00e9 Mobutu, as he wanted to avoid the corruption associated with his country. Instead, he is hired by the mayor of a small village, Marly-Gomont, in northern France. He tells his family that he got a job in a city north of Paris, France. His wife Anne and their two children, Sivi and Kamini, are disappointed to learn that they are living in a rural village, far from the excitement of Paris. His decision to live in France is mainly motivated by the hope of a better education for his children, but he also hopes to apply for French citizenship. Seyolo and his family struggle to adapt to new life as locals - unfamiliar with African professionals - fear newcomers, children are bullied at school, and Seyolo's practice struggles to survive as locals prefer to go to the next village whenever they need a doctor, instead of being visited by a \"wizard\". Seyolo and Anne have a heated argument in front of relatives who have come for a visit, during which Seyolo reluctantly promises that they will eventually move to Brussels, where some of their relatives live. However, Seyolo and his family end up winning the trust of the villagers, and his practice becomes a success after he delivers the baby to a local farmer.\n\nFollowing Seyolo's reputation and popularity, he tells the mayor that he wants to stay in Marly-Gomont for the long term. That same evening, the mayor and his wife are having dinner at the Zantokos' house, and the mayor mentions his happiness that Seyolo is in the village. Anne is shocked and angry at this revelation, for Seyolo had promised to move to Brussels and had not told Anne that he had accepted the mayor's request to stay in Marly-Gomont. Anne leaves to stay in Brussels with her family and the couple's relationship is in danger.\n\nMeanwhile, in Marly-Gomont, Seyolo is arrested by French police for immigration irregularities, days before his French citizenship application is approved, and he is forced to stop working. Anne finally returns and agrees to stay with Seyolo in Marly-Gomont. The only hope for Seyolo and his family is that the current mayor will be reelected, although his opponent, Lavigne, is leading the polls and is determined to prevent Seyolo from practicing in the village, preferring to hire a doctor of French origin. . However, Sivi is a talented soccer player and wins the hearts of the community, helping the local team make progress in the league alone. Seyolo and his children devise a plan to show residents that if Lavigne wins the election, the family will have to leave Marly-Gomont. Residents, upset over the prospect of losing the best football player, end up voting, and the incumbent mayor is reelected. Finally, the local school children play a play that re-enacts the arrival and eventual acceptance of Seyolo and his family, and they realize that they are loved by the entire community (except Lavigne, who leaves before the end of the show). Seyolo's office reopens and the family remains in Marly-Gomont.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Marc Zinga]] as Seyolo Zantoko\n* [[A\u00efssa Ma\u00efga]] as Anne Zantoko\n* Bayron Lebli as [[Kamini (musician)|Kamini Zantoko]]\n* M\u00e9dina Diarra as Sivi Zantoko\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]] as Jean\n* [[Jonathan Lambert (actor)|Jonathan Lambert]] as Lavigne\n* [[Mata Gabin]] as Mado\n* [[Sylvestre Amoussou]] as Uncle Beki\n* [[Riton Liebman]] as The driving teacher\n\n==See also==\n* [[Marly-Gomont (song)]], [[Kamini (musician)|Kamini]]'s ode to the small, rural village in Northern France where he grew up, Marly-Gomont. In the song, Kamini laments being from the only black family in town. The song became an Internet phenomenon and a number-one single in France.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|5555502}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:African Doctor, The}}\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films about race and ethnicity]]\n[[Category:Fictional physicians]]\n", "name_user": "47.62.196.114", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePlot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_African_Doctor"}
{"title_page": "Health information on the Internet", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=February 2020}}\n{{cleanup-confusing|date=April 2020}}\n{{cleanup-rewrite|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Desktop Computer - The Future for Medicine (FDA 095) (8249708093).jpg|thumb|right|A 1984 United States advertisement for access to health information with the 1980s [[Apple III]]]]\n'''Health information on the Internet''' refers to all health-related information communicated through or available on the [[Internet]].\n\n==Introduction==\nThe [[Internet]] can be a useful tool for finding health information in an easily accessible way to the general [[public]]. In the late 1990s, researchers noted an increase in [[Internet]] users' access to health-related content despite the variation in the quality of information, level of accessibility and overall health literacy.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Risk A, Petersen C | title = Health information on the internet: quality issues and international initiatives | journal = JAMA | volume = 287 | issue = 20 | pages = 2713\u20135 | year = 2002 | pmid = 12020308 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1001/jama.287.20.2713 }}</ref> Moreover, access to health information does not guarantee that such information will be easier to understand since '''health literacy''' is not always well understood.  \n\nIt is believed that [[Patient|patients]] who know their personal [[medical history]] may learn and interpret this information in a way that benefits them.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beaudin JS, Intille SS, Morris ME | title = To track or not to track: user reactions to concepts in longitudinal health monitoring | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 8 | issue = 4 | pages = e29 | year = 2006 | pmid = 17236264 | pmc = 1794006 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.8.4.e29 }}</ref> However, this is not always the case, as online health information may not be [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Risk A, Petersen C | title = Health information on the internet: quality issues and international initiatives | journal = JAMA | volume = 287 | issue = 20 | pages = 2713\u20135 | year = 2002 | pmid = 12020308 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1001/jama.287.20.2713 }}</ref> [[Physician|Physicians]] worry that patients who conduct Internet research on their medical history are at risk of being misinformed.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Robeznieks A | title = Getting personal. Legal liability, patient-data overload among issues making physicians uneasy over emergence of personal health records | journal = Modern Healthcare | volume = 37 | issue = 21 | pages = 40\u20132 | date = May 2007 | pmid = 17824189 }}</ref> In 2013, opinions about the relationship between health care providers and online health information were still being established.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Farnan JM, Snyder Sulmasy L, Worster BK, Chaudhry HJ, Rhyne JA, Arora VM | title = Online medical professionalism: patient and public relationships: policy statement from the American College of Physicians and the Federation of State Medical Boards | journal = Annals of Internal Medicine | volume = 158 | issue = 8 | pages = 620\u20137 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23579867 | doi = 10.7326/0003-4819-158-8-201304160-00100 }}</ref> According to a 2014 study, \"The flow of information has fundamentally changed, and physicians have less control over health information relayed to patients. Not surprisingly, this paradigm shift has elicited varied and sometimes conflicting views about the value of the Internet as a tool to improve health care.\"<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tonsaker T, Bartlett G, Trpkov C | title = Health information on the Internet: gold mine or minefield? | journal = Canadian Family Physician Medecin de Famille Canadien | volume = 60 | issue = 5 | pages = 407\u20138 | date = May 2014 | pmid = 24828994 | pmc = 4020634 }}</ref> \n\n=== Importance of the physician-patient relationship ===\nPhysicians often have difficulty explaining complicated medical concepts to patients, who often have difficulty understanding medical explanations. Physicians may use medical terms that patients do not understand but would like to learn.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Castro CM, Wilson C, Wang F, Schillinger D | title = Babel babble: physicians' use of unclarified medical jargon with patients | journal = American Journal of Health Behavior | volume = 31 Suppl 1 | pages = S85-95 | date = Sep\u2013Oct 2007 | pmid = 17931142 | doi = 10.5993/ajhb.31.s1.11 }}</ref> A consensus exists that patients should have [[shared decision making]], meaning that patients should be able to make informed decisions about the direction of their medical treatment in collaboration with their physician.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Braddock CH, Edwards KA, Hasenberg NM, Laidley TL, Levinson W | title = Informed decision making in outpatient practice: time to get back to basics | journal = JAMA | volume = 282 | issue = 24 | pages = 2313\u201320 | date = 22 December 1999 | pmid = 10612318 | doi = 10.1001/jama.282.24.2313 }}</ref> Rich, educated, and socially advantaged patients may enjoy the benefits of the [[Shared decision-making in medicine|shared decision making]] approach more than those with a lower [[Social class|socioeconomic class]] or [[Minority group|minority]] status.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fiscella K, Epstein RM | title = So much to do, so little time: care for the socially disadvantaged and the 15-minute visit | journal = Archives of Internal Medicine | volume = 168 | issue = 17 | pages = 1843\u201352 | date = September 2008 | pmid = 18809810 | pmc = 2606692 | doi = 10.1001/archinte.168.17.1843 }}</ref>\n\nA patient's naive understanding of their health contributes to a range of issues, including, but not limited to, the tendency to not adhere to the physician's medical advice or miss medical appointments.<ref name=\"Wicks 2010\">A better source should be used to support this claim, although this source is good enough for how it is used here. \n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Wicks P, Massagli M, Frost J, Brownstein C, Okun S, Vaughan T, Bradley R, Heywood J | display-authors = 6 | title = Sharing health data for better outcomes on PatientsLikeMe | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 12 | issue = 2 | pages = e19 | date = June 2010 | pmid = 20542858 | pmc = 2956230 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.1549 }}</ref> Patients with limited access to health information are more likely to use [[complementary and alternative medicine]] and fail to inform their physician about it.<ref name=\"Wicks 2010\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Robinson A, McGrail MR | title = Disclosure of CAM use to medical practitioners: a review of qualitative and quantitative studies | journal = Complementary Therapies in Medicine | volume = 12 | issue = 2\u20133 | pages = 90\u20138 | date = Jun\u2013Sep 2004 | pmid = 15561518 | doi = 10.1016/j.ctim.2004.09.006 }}</ref> It is important to note that [[complementary and alternative medicine]] may not be  [[evidence-based medicine]]. While physicians can be trained to be more efficient in serving patients, there may also be some benefits in training patients to be more efficient while dealing with physicians. A study by Lorig in 2002 suggested that health care processes can be improved with efficient patient's behavior.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lorig K | title = Partnerships between expert patients and physicians | journal = Lancet | volume = 359 | issue = 9309 | pages = 814\u20135 | date = March 2002 | pmid = 11897275 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)07959-X | url = https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/de6b0f7a8864da61cc0f11b61b1e54bc00345c9b }}</ref>\n\n=== Online Resources ===\n==== Social Platforms ====\nVarious social forums exist in which anyone can have conversations about health with their peers. Such forums are especially popular among patients who seek to have conversations about shared medical concerns with others.<ref name=\"Eysenbach 2004\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Eysenbach G, Powell J, Englesakis M, Rizo C, Stern A | title = Health related virtual communities and electronic support groups: systematic review of the effects of online peer to peer interactions | journal = BMJ | volume = 328 | issue = 7449 | pages = 1166 | date = May 2004 | pmid = 15142921 | pmc = 411092 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.328.7449.1166 }}</ref> Those who participate in online communities that discuss health issues report feeling relief about their health worries, perceiving more control over their health and medical condition, having more medical knowledge, and having more personal agency overall.<ref>{{cite journal| vauthors = Barak A, Boniel-Nissim M, Suler J |title=Fostering empowerment in online support groups|journal=Computers in Human Behavior|date=September 2008|volume=24|issue=5|pages=1867\u20131883|doi=10.1016/j.chb.2008.02.004}}</ref>\n====Social Media ====\nSome research has failed to find evidence to validate physicians' concerns that patients typically receive misinformation online or use health information to inappropriately conduct [[self diagnosis]].<ref name=\"Eysenbach 2004\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ahmad F, Hudak PL, Bercovitz K, Hollenberg E, Levinson W | title = Are physicians ready for patients with Internet-based health information? | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages = e22 | date = September 2006 | pmid = 17032638 | pmc = 2018833 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.8.3.e22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Crocco AG, Villasis-Keever M, Jadad AR | title = Analysis of cases of harm associated with use of health information on the internet | journal = JAMA | volume = 287 | issue = 21 | pages = 2869\u201371 | date = June 2002 | pmid = 12038937 | doi = 10.1001/jama.287.21.2869 }}</ref> Patients with chronic diseases who use the Internet to get health-related information often acquire good skills to judge the quality of information that they find.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stevenson FA, Kerr C, Murray E, Nazareth I | title = Information from the Internet and the doctor-patient relationship: the patient perspective--a qualitative study | journal = BMC Family Practice | volume = 8 | pages = 47 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17705836 | pmc = 2041946 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2296-8-47 }}</ref>\n\n[[Social media]] channels have been noted as places that physicians can visit to get insight on patient thoughts.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Verhoef LM, Van de Belt TH, Engelen LJ, Schoonhoven L, Kool RB | title = Social media and rating sites as tools to understanding quality of care: a scoping review | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 16 | issue = 2 | pages = e56 | date = February 2014 | pmid = 24566844 | pmc = 3961699 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.3024 }}</ref> Patients have increasingly turned to social media for health information, sometimes of dubious quality.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Prybutok G, Ryan S | title = Social media: the key to health information access for 18- to 30-year-old college students | journal = Computers, Informatics, Nursing | volume = 33 | issue = 4 | pages = 132\u201341 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25887107 | doi = 10.1097/CIN.0000000000000147 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lau AY, Siek KA, Fernandez-Luque L, Tange H, Chhanabhai P, Li SY, Elkin PL, Arjabi A, Walczowski L, Ang CS, Eysenbach G | display-authors = 6 | title = The role of social media for patients and consumer health. Contribution of the IMIA Consumer Health Informatics Working Group | journal = Yearbook of Medical Informatics | volume = 6 | issue = 1 | pages = 131\u20138 | date = 2011-01-01 | pmid = 21938338 | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/51662040 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fern\u00e1ndez-Luque L, Bau T | title = Health and social media: perfect storm of information | journal = Healthcare Informatics Research | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 67\u201373 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25995958 | pmc = 4434065 | doi = 10.4258/hir.2015.21.2.67 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Helve O, Kattelus M, Norhomaa S, Saarni S | title = [Health information and social media: the doctor as a primary school teacher again] | journal = Duodecim; Laaketieteellinen Aikakauskirja | volume = 131 | issue = 21 | pages = 2003\u20138 | date = 2015-01-01 | pmid = 26677551 }}</ref> Several studies have used social media to gather data on patients' [[adverse drug reaction]]s (ADRs), with generally promising results.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sarker A, Ginn R, Nikfarjam A, O'Connor K, Smith K, Jayaraman S, Upadhaya T, Gonzalez G | display-authors = 6 | title = Utilizing social media data for pharmacovigilance: A review | journal = Journal of Biomedical Informatics | volume = 54 | pages = 202\u201312 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25720841 | pmc = 4408239 | doi = 10.1016/j.jbi.2015.02.004 }}</ref>\n\nVarious commercial organizations use health information gathered from the Internet. The use of health information gathered from social media has been described as raising serious ethical and privacy concerns<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Denecke K, Bamidis P, Bond C, Gabarron E, Househ M, Lau AY, Mayer MA, Merolli M, Hansen M | display-authors = 6 | title = Ethical Issues of Social Media Usage in Healthcare | journal = Yearbook of Medical Informatics | volume = 10 | issue = 1 | pages = 137\u201347 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26293861 | pmc = 4587037 | doi = 10.15265/IY-2015-001 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Moorhead SA, Hazlett DE, Harrison L, Carroll JK, Irwin A, Hoving C | title = A new dimension of health care: systematic review of the uses, benefits, and limitations of social media for health communication | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = e85 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23615206 | pmc = 3636326 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.1933 }}</ref>, including the risk of accidental violations of patient privacy by healthcare providers.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ventola CL | title = Social media and health care professionals: benefits, risks, and best practices | journal = P & T | volume = 39 | issue = 7 | pages = 491\u2013520 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 25083128 | pmc = 4103576 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Shay DF | title = Physician use of social media: navigating the risks. Establish social media guidelines to protect health information, and reputation of practice and physicians | journal = Medical Economics | volume = 91 | issue = 16 | pages = 44\u20136 | date = August 2014 | pmid = 25509476 }}</ref>\n\n====Academic medical literature====\nThe written record of peer-reviewed medical consensus is stored in [[scientific journals]]. There has been an [[academic journal publishing reform]] since the advent of [[electronic publishing]]. Some journal has adopted an open-access<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://qims.amegroups.com/|title=Home - Quantitative Imaging in Medicine and Surgery|website=qims.amegroups.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jmirpublications.com/|title=JMIR Publications|website=www.jmirpublications.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> policy, and others have not<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.lww.com/nuclearmedicinecomm/Pages/aboutthejournal.aspx|title=About the Journal : Nuclear Medicine Communications|website=journals.lww.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. The open-access policy has significantly increased the accessibility of professional health information to researchers, physicians, and the public through the Internet. However, it is essential to note that some of the academic medical literature may not be peer-reviewed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medrxiv.org/|title=medRxiv.org - the preprint server for Health Sciences|website=www.medrxiv.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biorxiv.org/about-biorxiv|title=Advancing the sharing of research results for the life sciences|website=www.biorxiv.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>, and the users are advised to exercise caution when reading health-related articles from such websites.\n\n<br />\n==Quality==\nThe nature of health-related information available on the Internet is complex, and its quality varies greatly by source.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fahy E, Hardikar R, Fox A, Mackay S | title = Quality of patient health information on the Internet: reviewing a complex and evolving landscape | journal = The Australasian Medical Journal | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = 24\u20138 | year = 2014 | pmid = 24567763 | pmc = 3920473 | doi = 10.4066/AMJ.2014.1900 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Purcell GP, Wilson P, Delamothe T | title = The quality of health information on the internet | journal = BMJ | volume = 324 | issue = 7337 | pages = 557\u20138 | date = March 2002 | pmid = 11884303 | pmc = 1122494 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.324.7337.557 }}</ref><ref>Khosrowjerdi, M. (2016). A review of theory-driven models of trust in the online health context. IFLA Journal, 42(3): pp. 189-206. http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0340035216659299</ref> The standards for ensuring quality control on the Internet have been criticized{{Citation needed}}, and no single standard is universally accepted<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Jadad AR, Gagliardi A|date=February 1998|title=Rating health information on the Internet: navigating to knowledge or to Babel?|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/676606723782fbb79de6c24c49dd179c257fe3c3|journal=JAMA|volume=279|issue=8|pages=611\u20134|doi=10.1001/jama.279.8.611|pmc=|pmid=9486757}}</ref>. Many researchers have investigated this issue in detail resulting in a wide range of theories from different disciplines{{Citation needed}}.\n\n<br />\n\n\n==Personal health information==\nFor many applications, people wish to use health information on the Internet to give insight about a personal health concern. Because of this, the goal is often to use the Internet to find information described in a person's [[medical record]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tonsaker T, Bartlett G, Trpkov C | title = Health information on the Internet: gold mine or minefield? | journal = Canadian Family Physician Medecin de Famille Canadien | volume = 60 | issue = 5 | pages = 407\u20138 | date = May 2014 | pmid = 24828994 | pmc = 4020634 }}</ref> Since the advent of [[electronic media]], medical records have been increasingly kept as [[electronic medical records]].{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} If electronic medical records were shared online, then it would be easy to match those with information and conduct a range of research.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Pagliari C, Detmer D, Singleton P | title = Potential of electronic personal health records | journal = BMJ | volume = 335 | issue = 7615 | pages = 330\u20133 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17703042 | pmc = 1949437 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.39279.482963.AD }}</ref>  However, all medical records are [[protected health information]] because sharing personal health information exposes an individual to a range of harms that result from a violation of their [[expectation of privacy]].<ref>{{Cite book| veditors = Nass SJ, Levit LA, Gostin LO |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK9579/ |title=The Value and Importance of Health Information Privacy | collaboration = Institute of Medicine (US) Committee on Health Research and the Privacy of Health Information: The HIPAA Privacy Rule |date=2009|publisher=National Academies Press (US)|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThere is currently a broad international debate about how to balance patient and commercial medicine demands for personal health information with an individual's needs for safety and respect.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kaplan RM, Babad YM | title = Balancing influence between actors in healthcare decision making | journal = BMC Health Services Research | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 85 | date = April 2011 | pmid = 21504599 | pmc = 3108374 | doi = 10.1186/1472-6963-11-85 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| author = National Research Council (US) Committee on Enhancing the Internet for Health Applications: Technical Requirements and Implementation Strategies |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK44714/|title=Health Applications of the Internet|date=2000|publisher=National Academies Press (US)|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Electronic medical records===\n{{main|Electronic medical record}}\nAn electronic medical record is a [[medical record]] stored on [[electronic media]]<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tang PC, Ash JS, Bates DW, Overhage JM, Sands DZ | title = Personal health records: definitions, benefits, and strategies for overcoming barriers to adoption | journal = Journal of the American Medical Informatics Association | volume = 13 | issue = 2 | pages = 121\u20136 | date = 1 March 2006 | pmid = 16357345 | pmc = 1447551 | doi = 10.1197/jamia.M2025 }}</ref>, for example, computer servers or hard-drives. \n\n===De-identification===\n{{main|De-identification}}\nDe-identification is an attempt to remove the identifiable patient's identifiable information from their medical records with the intent of making the information transferable without compromising the patient's identity{{citation needed}}. The closer the data is to [[anonymization]], the lesser is its value to those who want it{{citation needed}}. In general, a patient's data is rarely fully anonymized{{need citation}}. Many controversies exist regarding the de-identification of patient's data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-professionals/privacy/special-topics/de-identification/index.html|title=Methods for De-identification of PHI|author=Office for CivilRights (OCR)|date=2012-09-07|website=HHS.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n===Research using personal health information===\nThere is a high commercial<ref>{{Cite journal|vauthors=Bundorf MK, Baker L, Singer S, Wagner T|date=March 2004|title=Consumer Demand for Health Information on the Internet|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w10386|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> demand for accessing extensive collections of various types of personal health care information. \n\n===Distribution of collections of personal health information===\nIn 2014 [[National Health Service]] (NHS) in the United Kingdom proposed to sell patients' personal health information<ref>{{cite news|last=Ramesh|first=Randeep|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jan/19/nhs-patient-data-available-companies-buy|title=NHS patient data to be made available for sale to drug and insurance firms|date=19 January 2014|work=theguardian.com|access-date=31 March 2014|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>. However, in 2013, various groups had already expressed worries over dangers resulting from the distribution of patient's identifiable information along with their medical history<ref>{{cite news|last=Doctorow|first=Cory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2013/jun/05/data-protection-eu-anonymous|title=Data protection in the EU: the certainty of uncertainty|date=5 June 2013|work=theguardian.com|access-date=31 March 2014|authorlink=Cory Doctorow|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>.<br />\n<br />\n\n==Major providers of health information on the Internet==\n===PubMed===\n{{main|PubMed}}\nPubMed is a free search engine primarily listing the [[MEDLINE]] database of peer-reviewed references and abstracts on life sciences and biomedical topics. The [[United States National Library of Medicine]] at the [[National Institutes of Health]] maintains the database. When the reader searches and tries to access a manuscript of interest, they are directed to the website of the respective journal where the document was originally published by a publisher.\n\n===Wikipedia===\n{{main|Health information on Wikipedia}}\nIn 2014 Wikipedia was described as \"the leading single source of healthcare information for patients\nand healthcare professionals\".<ref>Note - sketchy link requires registration. {{cite book|title=Engaging patients through social media Is healthcare ready for empowered and digitally demanding patients?|year=2014|publisher=[[IMS Health]]|pages=16\u201326|chapter-url=http://www.imshealth.com/portal/site/imshealth/menuitem.762a961826aad98f53c753c71ad8c22a/?vgnextoid=505cde0fdbc73410VgnVCM10000076192ca2RCRD&vgnextchannel=736de5fda6370410VgnVCM10000076192ca2RCRD&vgnextfmt=default|author=IMS Health|access-date=22 January 2014|chapter=The use of Wikipedia in Health Care|author-link=IMS Health}} Further cited in\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.npr.org/2014/02/08/273680018/dr-wikipedia-the-double-edged-sword-of-crowd-sourced-medicine |title=Dr. Wikipedia: The 'Double-Edged Sword' Of Crowd-Sourced Medicine |author=NPR staff |work=npr.org |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=8 February 2014 |access-date=10 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://qz.com/171162/americas-future-doctors-are-starting-their-careers-by-saving-wikipedia/ |title=America's future doctors are starting their careers by saving Wikipedia |first=Rachel |last=Feltman | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Quartz (publication)|qz.com]] |date=28 January 2014 |access-date=5 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.newsmax.com/Reagan/Doctors-Wikipedia-online-healthcare/2014/01/31/id/550164 |title=Wikipedia Shouldn't be Doctors' online healthcare source |first=Michael |last=Reagan | name-list-format = vanc  |authorlink=Michael Reagan |work=[[Newsmax Media|newsmax.com]] |date=31 Jan 2014 |access-date=5 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/820249 |title=Doctors, Not Just Patients, Use Wikipedia, Too: IMS Report |first=Miriam E. |last=Tucker | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Medscape]] |date=5 February 2014 |access-date=7 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/doctors-1-source-for-healthcare-information-wikipedia/284206/ |title=Doctors' #1 Source for Healthcare Information: Wikipedia |first=Julie  |last=Beck | name-list-format = vanc  |work=[[The Atlantic|theatlantic.com]] |date=5 March 2014 |access-date=5 March 2014}}\n</ref> However, the information available on Wikipedia may not be peer-reviewed.\n\n===Other wikis===\n{{main|List of medical wikis}}<br />\n==Regulation==\nIn the United States, the [[Food and Drug Administration]] offers guidance for health industry organizations that share information online.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://blogs.fda.gov/fdavoice/index.php/2014/06/fda-issues-draft-guidances-for-industry-on-social-media-and-internet-communications-about-medical-products-designed-with-patients-in-mind/ |title=FDA Issues Draft Guidances for Industry on Social Media and Internet Communications About Medical Products: Designed with Patients in Mind |author=FDA Voice |work=blogs.fda.gov |date=17 June 2014 |access-date=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.fda.gov/AboutFDA/CentersOffices/OfficeofMedicalProductsandTobacco/CDER/ucm397791.htm |title=About the Center for Drug Evaluation and Research &#62; For Industry: Using Social Media |author=Food and Drug Administration |work=fda.gov |date=2014-07-07 |access-date=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}} \n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/evaluatinghealthinformation.html Evaluating Health Information] by [[MedlinePlus]]\n*[https://www.infocompile.com/2019/07/best-10-websites-for-health-news-and-Articles.html 10 Best Websites for Health News And Articles Online] by [https://www.infocompile.com/ InfoCompile]\n*[https://www.fda.gov/Drugs/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/BuyingUsingMedicineSafely/BuyingMedicinesOvertheInternet/ucm202863.htm How to Evaluate Health Information on the Internet] by the [[Food and Drug Administration]]\n\n{{Telemedicine navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Academic works about medicine]]\n[[Category:Online services]]\n[[Category:Electronic publishing]]\n[[Category:Works about health|Internet]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=February 2020}}\n{{cleanup-confusing|date=April 2020}}\n{{cleanup-rewrite|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Desktop Computer - The Future for Medicine (FDA 095) (8249708093).jpg|thumb|right|A 1984 United States advertisement for access to health information with the 1980s [[Apple III]]]]\n'''Health information on the Internet''' refers to all health-related information communicated through or available on the [[Internet]].\n\n==Introduction==\nThe [[Internet]] can be a useful tool for finding health information in an easily accessible way to the general [[public]]. In the late 1990s, researchers noted an increase in [[Internet]] users' access to health-related content despite the variation in the quality of information, level of accessibility and overall health literacy.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Risk A, Petersen C | title = Health information on the internet: quality issues and international initiatives | journal = JAMA | volume = 287 | issue = 20 | pages = 2713\u20135 | year = 2002 | pmid = 12020308 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1001/jama.287.20.2713 }}</ref> Moreover, access to health information does not guarantee that such information will be easier to understand since '''health literacy''' is not always well understood.  \n\nIt is believed that [[Patient|patients]] who know their personal [[medical history]] may learn and interpret this information in a way that benefits them.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beaudin JS, Intille SS, Morris ME | title = To track or not to track: user reactions to concepts in longitudinal health monitoring | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 8 | issue = 4 | pages = e29 | year = 2006 | pmid = 17236264 | pmc = 1794006 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.8.4.e29 }}</ref> However, this is not always the case, as online health information may not be [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Risk A, Petersen C | title = Health information on the internet: quality issues and international initiatives | journal = JAMA | volume = 287 | issue = 20 | pages = 2713\u20135 | year = 2002 | pmid = 12020308 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1001/jama.287.20.2713 }}</ref> [[Physician|Physicians]] worry that patients who conduct Internet research on their medical history are at risk of being misinformed.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Robeznieks A | title = Getting personal. Legal liability, patient-data overload among issues making physicians uneasy over emergence of personal health records | journal = Modern Healthcare | volume = 37 | issue = 21 | pages = 40\u20132 | date = May 2007 | pmid = 17824189 }}</ref> In 2013, opinions about the relationship between health care providers and online health information were still being established.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Farnan JM, Snyder Sulmasy L, Worster BK, Chaudhry HJ, Rhyne JA, Arora VM | title = Online medical professionalism: patient and public relationships: policy statement from the American College of Physicians and the Federation of State Medical Boards | journal = Annals of Internal Medicine | volume = 158 | issue = 8 | pages = 620\u20137 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23579867 | doi = 10.7326/0003-4819-158-8-201304160-00100 }}</ref> According to a 2014 study, \"The flow of information has fundamentally changed, and physicians have less control over health information relayed to patients. Not surprisingly, this paradigm shift has elicited varied and sometimes conflicting views about the value of the Internet as a tool to improve health care.\"<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tonsaker T, Bartlett G, Trpkov C | title = Health information on the Internet: gold mine or minefield? | journal = Canadian Family Physician Medecin de Famille Canadien | volume = 60 | issue = 5 | pages = 407\u20138 | date = May 2014 | pmid = 24828994 | pmc = 4020634 }}</ref> \n\n=== Importance of the physician-patient relationship ===\nPhysicians often have difficulty explaining complicated medical concepts to patients, who often have difficulty understanding medical explanations. Physicians may use medical terms that patients do not understand but would like to learn.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Castro CM, Wilson C, Wang F, Schillinger D | title = Babel babble: physicians' use of unclarified medical jargon with patients | journal = American Journal of Health Behavior | volume = 31 Suppl 1 | pages = S85-95 | date = Sep\u2013Oct 2007 | pmid = 17931142 | doi = 10.5993/ajhb.31.s1.11 }}</ref> A consensus exists that patients should have [[shared decision making]], meaning that patients should be able to make informed decisions about the direction of their medical treatment in collaboration with their physician.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Braddock CH, Edwards KA, Hasenberg NM, Laidley TL, Levinson W | title = Informed decision making in outpatient practice: time to get back to basics | journal = JAMA | volume = 282 | issue = 24 | pages = 2313\u201320 | date = 22 December 1999 | pmid = 10612318 | doi = 10.1001/jama.282.24.2313 }}</ref> Rich, educated, and socially advantaged patients may enjoy the benefits of the [[Shared decision-making in medicine|shared decision making]] approach more than those with a lower [[Social class|socioeconomic class]] or [[Minority group|minority]] status.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fiscella K, Epstein RM | title = So much to do, so little time: care for the socially disadvantaged and the 15-minute visit | journal = Archives of Internal Medicine | volume = 168 | issue = 17 | pages = 1843\u201352 | date = September 2008 | pmid = 18809810 | pmc = 2606692 | doi = 10.1001/archinte.168.17.1843 }}</ref>\n\nA patient's naive understanding of their health contributes to a range of issues, including, but not limited to, the tendency to not adhere to the physician's medical advice or miss medical appointments.<ref name=\"Wicks 2010\">A better source should be used to support this claim, although this source is good enough for how it is used here. \n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Wicks P, Massagli M, Frost J, Brownstein C, Okun S, Vaughan T, Bradley R, Heywood J | display-authors = 6 | title = Sharing health data for better outcomes on PatientsLikeMe | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 12 | issue = 2 | pages = e19 | date = June 2010 | pmid = 20542858 | pmc = 2956230 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.1549 }}</ref> Patients with limited access to health information are more likely to use [[complementary and alternative medicine]] and fail to inform their physician about it.<ref name=\"Wicks 2010\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Robinson A, McGrail MR | title = Disclosure of CAM use to medical practitioners: a review of qualitative and quantitative studies | journal = Complementary Therapies in Medicine | volume = 12 | issue = 2\u20133 | pages = 90\u20138 | date = Jun\u2013Sep 2004 | pmid = 15561518 | doi = 10.1016/j.ctim.2004.09.006 }}</ref> It is important to note that [[complementary and alternative medicine]] may not be  [[evidence-based medicine]]. While physicians can be trained to be more efficient in serving patients, there may also be some benefits in training patients to be more efficient while dealing with physicians. A study by Lorig in 2002 suggested that health care processes can be improved with efficient patient's behavior.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lorig K | title = Partnerships between expert patients and physicians | journal = Lancet | volume = 359 | issue = 9309 | pages = 814\u20135 | date = March 2002 | pmid = 11897275 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)07959-X | url = https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/de6b0f7a8864da61cc0f11b61b1e54bc00345c9b }}</ref>\n\n=== Online Resources ===\n==== Social Platforms ====\nVarious social forums exist in which anyone can have conversations about health with their peers. Such forums are especially popular among patients who seek to have conversations about shared medical concerns with others.<ref name=\"Eysenbach 2004\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Eysenbach G, Powell J, Englesakis M, Rizo C, Stern A | title = Health related virtual communities and electronic support groups: systematic review of the effects of online peer to peer interactions | journal = BMJ | volume = 328 | issue = 7449 | pages = 1166 | date = May 2004 | pmid = 15142921 | pmc = 411092 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.328.7449.1166 }}</ref> Those who participate in online communities that discuss health issues report feeling relief about their health worries, perceiving more control over their health and medical condition, having more medical knowledge, and having more personal agency overall.<ref>{{cite journal| vauthors = Barak A, Boniel-Nissim M, Suler J |title=Fostering empowerment in online support groups|journal=Computers in Human Behavior|date=September 2008|volume=24|issue=5|pages=1867\u20131883|doi=10.1016/j.chb.2008.02.004}}</ref>\n====Social Media ====\nSome research has failed to find evidence to validate physicians' concerns that patients typically receive misinformation online or use health information to inappropriately conduct [[self diagnosis]].<ref name=\"Eysenbach 2004\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ahmad F, Hudak PL, Bercovitz K, Hollenberg E, Levinson W | title = Are physicians ready for patients with Internet-based health information? | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages = e22 | date = September 2006 | pmid = 17032638 | pmc = 2018833 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.8.3.e22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Crocco AG, Villasis-Keever M, Jadad AR | title = Analysis of cases of harm associated with use of health information on the internet | journal = JAMA | volume = 287 | issue = 21 | pages = 2869\u201371 | date = June 2002 | pmid = 12038937 | doi = 10.1001/jama.287.21.2869 }}</ref> Patients with chronic diseases who use the Internet to get health-related information often acquire good skills to judge the quality of information that they find.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stevenson FA, Kerr C, Murray E, Nazareth I | title = Information from the Internet and the doctor-patient relationship: the patient perspective--a qualitative study | journal = BMC Family Practice | volume = 8 | pages = 47 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17705836 | pmc = 2041946 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2296-8-47 }}</ref>\n\n[[Social media]] channels have been noted as places that physicians can visit to get insight on patient thoughts.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Verhoef LM, Van de Belt TH, Engelen LJ, Schoonhoven L, Kool RB | title = Social media and rating sites as tools to understanding quality of care: a scoping review | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 16 | issue = 2 | pages = e56 | date = February 2014 | pmid = 24566844 | pmc = 3961699 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.3024 }}</ref> Patients have increasingly turned to social media for health information, sometimes of dubious quality.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Prybutok G, Ryan S | title = Social media: the key to health information access for 18- to 30-year-old college students | journal = Computers, Informatics, Nursing | volume = 33 | issue = 4 | pages = 132\u201341 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25887107 | doi = 10.1097/CIN.0000000000000147 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lau AY, Siek KA, Fernandez-Luque L, Tange H, Chhanabhai P, Li SY, Elkin PL, Arjabi A, Walczowski L, Ang CS, Eysenbach G | display-authors = 6 | title = The role of social media for patients and consumer health. Contribution of the IMIA Consumer Health Informatics Working Group | journal = Yearbook of Medical Informatics | volume = 6 | issue = 1 | pages = 131\u20138 | date = 2011-01-01 | pmid = 21938338 | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/51662040 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fern\u00e1ndez-Luque L, Bau T | title = Health and social media: perfect storm of information | journal = Healthcare Informatics Research | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 67\u201373 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25995958 | pmc = 4434065 | doi = 10.4258/hir.2015.21.2.67 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Helve O, Kattelus M, Norhomaa S, Saarni S | title = [Health information and social media: the doctor as a primary school teacher again] | journal = Duodecim; Laaketieteellinen Aikakauskirja | volume = 131 | issue = 21 | pages = 2003\u20138 | date = 2015-01-01 | pmid = 26677551 }}</ref> Several studies have used social media to gather data on patients' [[adverse drug reaction]]s (ADRs), with generally promising results.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Sarker A, Ginn R, Nikfarjam A, O'Connor K, Smith K, Jayaraman S, Upadhaya T, Gonzalez G | display-authors = 6 | title = Utilizing social media data for pharmacovigilance: A review | journal = Journal of Biomedical Informatics | volume = 54 | pages = 202\u201312 | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25720841 | pmc = 4408239 | doi = 10.1016/j.jbi.2015.02.004 }}</ref>\n\nVarious commercial organizations use health information gathered from the Internet. The use of health information gathered from social media has been described as raising serious ethical and privacy concerns<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Denecke K, Bamidis P, Bond C, Gabarron E, Househ M, Lau AY, Mayer MA, Merolli M, Hansen M | display-authors = 6 | title = Ethical Issues of Social Media Usage in Healthcare | journal = Yearbook of Medical Informatics | volume = 10 | issue = 1 | pages = 137\u201347 | date = August 2015 | pmid = 26293861 | pmc = 4587037 | doi = 10.15265/IY-2015-001 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Moorhead SA, Hazlett DE, Harrison L, Carroll JK, Irwin A, Hoving C | title = A new dimension of health care: systematic review of the uses, benefits, and limitations of social media for health communication | journal = Journal of Medical Internet Research | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = e85 | date = April 2013 | pmid = 23615206 | pmc = 3636326 | doi = 10.2196/jmir.1933 }}</ref>, including the risk of accidental violations of patient privacy by healthcare providers.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ventola CL | title = Social media and health care professionals: benefits, risks, and best practices | journal = P & T | volume = 39 | issue = 7 | pages = 491\u2013520 | date = July 2014 | pmid = 25083128 | pmc = 4103576 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Shay DF | title = Physician use of social media: navigating the risks. Establish social media guidelines to protect health information, and reputation of practice and physicians | journal = Medical Economics | volume = 91 | issue = 16 | pages = 44\u20136 | date = August 2014 | pmid = 25509476 }}</ref>\n\n====Academic medical literature====\nThe written record of peer-reviewed medical consensus is stored in [[scientific journals]]. There has been an [[academic journal publishing reform]] since the advent of [[electronic publishing]]. Some journal has adopted an open-access<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://qims.amegroups.com/|title=Home - Quantitative Imaging in Medicine and Surgery|website=qims.amegroups.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jmirpublications.com/|title=JMIR Publications|website=www.jmirpublications.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> policy, and others have not<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journals.lww.com/nuclearmedicinecomm/Pages/aboutthejournal.aspx|title=About the Journal : Nuclear Medicine Communications|website=journals.lww.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>. The open-access policy has significantly increased the accessibility of professional health information to researchers, physicians, and the public through the Internet. However, it is essential to note that some of the academic medical literature may not be peer-reviewed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medrxiv.org/|title=medRxiv.org - the preprint server for Health Sciences|website=www.medrxiv.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biorxiv.org/about-biorxiv|title=Advancing the sharing of research results for the life sciences|website=www.biorxiv.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>, and the users are advised to exercise caution when reading health-related articles from such websites.\n\n<br />\n==Quality==\nThe nature of health-related information available on the Internet is complex, and its quality varies greatly by source.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fahy E, Hardikar R, Fox A, Mackay S | title = Quality of patient health information on the Internet: reviewing a complex and evolving landscape | journal = The Australasian Medical Journal | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = 24\u20138 | year = 2014 | pmid = 24567763 | pmc = 3920473 | doi = 10.4066/AMJ.2014.1900 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Purcell GP, Wilson P, Delamothe T | title = The quality of health information on the internet | journal = BMJ | volume = 324 | issue = 7337 | pages = 557\u20138 | date = March 2002 | pmid = 11884303 | pmc = 1122494 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.324.7337.557 }}</ref><ref>Khosrowjerdi, M. (2016). A review of theory-driven models of trust in the online health context. IFLA Journal, 42(3): pp. 189-206. http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0340035216659299</ref> The standards for ensuring quality control on the Internet have been criticized{{Citation needed}}, and no single standard is universally accepted<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Jadad AR, Gagliardi A|date=February 1998|title=Rating health information on the Internet: navigating to knowledge or to Babel?|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/676606723782fbb79de6c24c49dd179c257fe3c3|journal=JAMA|volume=279|issue=8|pages=611\u20134|doi=10.1001/jama.279.8.611|pmc=|pmid=9486757}}</ref>. Many researchers have investigated this issue in detail resulting in a wide range of theories from different disciplines{{Citation needed}}.\n\n<br />\n\n\n==Personal health information==\nFor many applications, people wish to use health information on the Internet to give insight about a personal health concern. Because of this, the goal is often to use the Internet to find information described in a person's [[medical record]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tonsaker T, Bartlett G, Trpkov C | title = Health information on the Internet: gold mine or minefield? | journal = Canadian Family Physician Medecin de Famille Canadien | volume = 60 | issue = 5 | pages = 407\u20138 | date = May 2014 | pmid = 24828994 | pmc = 4020634 }}</ref> Since the advent of [[electronic media]], medical records have been increasingly kept as [[electronic medical records]].{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} If electronic medical records were shared online, then it would be easy to match those with information and conduct a range of research.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Pagliari C, Detmer D, Singleton P | title = Potential of electronic personal health records | journal = BMJ | volume = 335 | issue = 7615 | pages = 330\u20133 | date = August 2007 | pmid = 17703042 | pmc = 1949437 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.39279.482963.AD }}</ref>  However, all medical records are [[protected health information]] because sharing personal health information exposes an individual to a range of harms that result from a violation of their [[expectation of privacy]].<ref>{{Cite book| veditors = Nass SJ, Levit LA, Gostin LO |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK9579/ |title=The Value and Importance of Health Information Privacy | collaboration = Institute of Medicine (US) Committee on Health Research and the Privacy of Health Information: The HIPAA Privacy Rule |date=2009|publisher=National Academies Press (US)|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThere is currently a broad international debate about how to balance patient and commercial medicine demands for personal health information with an individual's needs for safety and respect.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kaplan RM, Babad YM | title = Balancing influence between actors in healthcare decision making | journal = BMC Health Services Research | volume = 11 | issue = 1 | pages = 85 | date = April 2011 | pmid = 21504599 | pmc = 3108374 | doi = 10.1186/1472-6963-11-85 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| author = National Research Council (US) Committee on Enhancing the Internet for Health Applications: Technical Requirements and Implementation Strategies |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK44714/|title=Health Applications of the Internet|date=2000|publisher=National Academies Press (US)|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Electronic medical records===\n{{main|Electronic medical record}}\nAn electronic medical record is a [[medical record]] stored on [[electronic media]]<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Tang PC, Ash JS, Bates DW, Overhage JM, Sands DZ | title = Personal health records: definitions, benefits, and strategies for overcoming barriers to adoption | journal = Journal of the American Medical Informatics Association | volume = 13 | issue = 2 | pages = 121\u20136 | date = 1 March 2006 | pmid = 16357345 | pmc = 1447551 | doi = 10.1197/jamia.M2025 }}</ref>, for example, computer servers or hard-drives. \n\n===De-identification===\n{{main|De-identification}}\nDe-identification is an attempt to remove the identifiable patient's identifiable information from their medical records with the intent of making the information transferable without compromising the patient's identity{{citation needed}}. The closer the data is to [[anonymization]], the lesser is its value to those who want it{{citation needed}}. In general, a patient's data is rarely fully anonymized{{need citation}}. Many controversies exist regarding the de-identification of patient's data.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-professionals/privacy/special-topics/de-identification/index.html|title=Methods for De-identification of PHI|author=Office for CivilRights (OCR)|date=2012-09-07|website=HHS.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n===Research using personal health information===\nThere is a high commercial<ref>{{Cite journal|vauthors=Bundorf MK, Baker L, Singer S, Wagner T|date=March 2004|title=Consumer Demand for Health Information on the Internet|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w10386|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> demand for accessing extensive collections of various types of personal health care information. \n\n===Distribution of collections of personal health information===\nIn 2014 [[National Health Service]] (NHS) in the United Kingdom proposed to sell patients' personal health information<ref>{{cite news|last=Ramesh|first=Randeep|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jan/19/nhs-patient-data-available-companies-buy|title=NHS patient data to be made available for sale to drug and insurance firms|date=19 January 2014|work=theguardian.com|access-date=31 March 2014|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>. However, in 2013, various groups had already expressed worries over dangers resulting from the distribution of patient's identifiable information along with their medical history<ref>{{cite news|last=Doctorow|first=Cory|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/blog/2013/jun/05/data-protection-eu-anonymous|title=Data protection in the EU: the certainty of uncertainty|date=5 June 2013|work=theguardian.com|access-date=31 March 2014|authorlink=Cory Doctorow|name-list-format=vanc}}</ref>.<br />\n\n==Major providers of health information on the Internet==\n===PubMed===\n{{main|PubMed}}\nPubMed is a free search engine primarily listing the [[MEDLINE]] database of peer-reviewed references and abstracts on life sciences and biomedical topics. The [[United States National Library of Medicine]] at the [[National Institutes of Health]] maintains the database. When the reader searches and tries to access a manuscript of interest, they are directed to the website of the respective journal where the document was originally published by a publisher.\n\n===Wikipedia===\n{{main|Health information on Wikipedia}}\nIn 2014 Wikipedia was described as \"the leading single source of healthcare information for patients\nand healthcare professionals\".<ref>Note - sketchy link requires registration. {{cite book|title=Engaging patients through social media Is healthcare ready for empowered and digitally demanding patients?|year=2014|publisher=[[IMS Health]]|pages=16\u201326|chapter-url=http://www.imshealth.com/portal/site/imshealth/menuitem.762a961826aad98f53c753c71ad8c22a/?vgnextoid=505cde0fdbc73410VgnVCM10000076192ca2RCRD&vgnextchannel=736de5fda6370410VgnVCM10000076192ca2RCRD&vgnextfmt=default|author=IMS Health|access-date=22 January 2014|chapter=The use of Wikipedia in Health Care|author-link=IMS Health}} Further cited in\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.npr.org/2014/02/08/273680018/dr-wikipedia-the-double-edged-sword-of-crowd-sourced-medicine |title=Dr. Wikipedia: The 'Double-Edged Sword' Of Crowd-Sourced Medicine |author=NPR staff |work=npr.org |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=8 February 2014 |access-date=10 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://qz.com/171162/americas-future-doctors-are-starting-their-careers-by-saving-wikipedia/ |title=America's future doctors are starting their careers by saving Wikipedia |first=Rachel |last=Feltman | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Quartz (publication)|qz.com]] |date=28 January 2014 |access-date=5 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.newsmax.com/Reagan/Doctors-Wikipedia-online-healthcare/2014/01/31/id/550164 |title=Wikipedia Shouldn't be Doctors' online healthcare source |first=Michael |last=Reagan | name-list-format = vanc  |authorlink=Michael Reagan |work=[[Newsmax Media|newsmax.com]] |date=31 Jan 2014 |access-date=5 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/820249 |title=Doctors, Not Just Patients, Use Wikipedia, Too: IMS Report |first=Miriam E. |last=Tucker | name-list-format = vanc |work=[[Medscape]] |date=5 February 2014 |access-date=7 February 2014}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2014/03/doctors-1-source-for-healthcare-information-wikipedia/284206/ |title=Doctors' #1 Source for Healthcare Information: Wikipedia |first=Julie  |last=Beck | name-list-format = vanc  |work=[[The Atlantic|theatlantic.com]] |date=5 March 2014 |access-date=5 March 2014}}\n</ref> However, the information available on Wikipedia may not be peer-reviewed.\n\n===Other wikis===\n{{main|List of medical wikis}}<br />\n==Regulation==\nIn the United States, the [[Food and Drug Administration]] offers guidance for health industry organizations that share information online.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://blogs.fda.gov/fdavoice/index.php/2014/06/fda-issues-draft-guidances-for-industry-on-social-media-and-internet-communications-about-medical-products-designed-with-patients-in-mind/ |title=FDA Issues Draft Guidances for Industry on Social Media and Internet Communications About Medical Products: Designed with Patients in Mind |author=FDA Voice |work=blogs.fda.gov |date=17 June 2014 |access-date=5 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.fda.gov/AboutFDA/CentersOffices/OfficeofMedicalProductsandTobacco/CDER/ucm397791.htm |title=About the Center for Drug Evaluation and Research &#62; For Industry: Using Social Media |author=Food and Drug Administration |work=fda.gov |date=2014-07-07 |access-date=5 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}} \n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/evaluatinghealthinformation.html Evaluating Health Information] by [[MedlinePlus]]\n*[https://www.infocompile.com/2019/07/best-10-websites-for-health-news-and-Articles.html 10 Best Websites for Health News And Articles Online] by [https://www.infocompile.com/ InfoCompile]\n*[https://www.fda.gov/Drugs/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/BuyingUsingMedicineSafely/BuyingMedicinesOvertheInternet/ucm202863.htm How to Evaluate Health Information on the Internet] by the [[Food and Drug Administration]]\n\n{{Telemedicine navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Academic works about medicine]]\n[[Category:Online services]]\n[[Category:Electronic publishing]]\n[[Category:Works about health|Internet]]\n", "name_user": "Earthianyogi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Health_information_on_the_Internet"}
